	// TF augments from base game (will be properly replaced later)
	/*  tl;dr: Plains inherits Flood plains as a legit terrainFeature.
	    In making this tileset, the goal had been absolute adherence to G&K entities w/o introducing new ones. The goal bent entities
	    a bit with new combo entities like Desert+Flood plains.png to patch in sprites with correct representation in U5 but yet
	    retaining the very same G&K behaviors. I'm doing a new quality pass updating bridges and find the dynamics of river limitations,
	    river/static-shaded coloring, proximity to land or water, it's time to do something that G&K should have done long ago: "Plains"
	    are now a legit occurence for Flood plains, vs only Desert (prob Civ V spec). By doing this, *I can negate tile edging* at coasts
	    which otherwise adds undesired edge gfx where a river should visibly flow through, since Plains are only used for path
	    terrainfeature tiles. Options are very limited - making a bridge into a special wonder dual land/water tile is an option,
	    including setting by use of canal improvement'ing. Not being concerned about random placement is a huge advantage. The block
	    below is duped from G&K w/ the single addition of Plains: */
	{
		"name": "Flood plains",
		"type": "TerrainFeature",
		"food": 2,
		"movementCost": 1,
		"defenceBonus": -0.1,
		"occursOn": ["Desert","Plains"],
		"uniques": ["Always Fertility [5] for Map Generation",
			"Considered [Food] when determining start locations",
			"Considered [Desirable] when determining start locations"]
	},


	// INFO //
	/* 	Terrainfeature manual tile edging hacks to add natural cornering edging as seen in original Ultima V. imo the attention to land
		detail seen within Ultima V is one of the massive visual features setting the game light years ahead of everyone else.
		There's a bunch of these within the sprite set that need importing, and manual conversion square->hex/square attention.

	[path|river TerrainDecor NAMING LOGIC]
		[path|river] {vertical is} {from} {heading towards} {to}
		Paths and rivers have 6 points to enter/exit. Depending on the tile route, 0-4 direction labels could be used.
		The scheme is a little convoluted though it is consistent and does work logically.
	*/

